BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 3-Section 2 (Introduction) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
2. INTRODUCTION 2.1 Scope. This statement ("Statement") shall apply to service under each Firm Gas Transportation Agreement, Interruptible Gas Transportation Agreement, and Park and Loan Agreement ("Agreement") entered between Shipper (as defined herein) and BBT Bamagas Intrastate, LLC, an Alabama Hinshaw pipeline (hereinafter referred to as "Transporter"), on the system of Transporter ("Transporter's System") pursuant to Subpart G of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations. Transporter's System consists of an approximately 52 mile long 30-inch pipeline from interconnections with Tennessee Gas Pipeline Company, LLC and BBT AlaTenn, LLC ("AlaTenn") near Barton, Alabama to delivery connections with three electric generation facilities, AlaTenn and BBT Tennessee River, LLC ("Trigas") all near Decatur, Alabama. AlaTenn and Trigas are affiliates of Transporter. 2.2 Availability. Transportation Service under this Statement is made available to any party (hereinafter referred to as "Shipper") for the Transportation of Gas by Transporter on Transporter's System pursuant to Subpart G of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations when: (a) Shipper desires Firm or Interruptible Transportation or Park and Loan Service; (b) Shipper has submitted a valid request in accordance with Section 5 hereof for service under this Statement and Transporter has available capacity to render such service; and (c) Shipper and Transporter have executed an Agreement for such service under this Statement.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 4-Section 3 (Definitions) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
3. DEFINITIONS 3.1 Definitions. As used herein, terms defined elsewhere shall have the meaning defined there and the following terms shall have the meaning defined below: (a) "British Thermal Unit" or "BTU" - The amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one (1) pound of water one degree Fahrenheit (1o F) at sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60o F). "MMBTU" shall mean one million (1,000,000) BTUs. (b) "Business Day" - Monday through Friday from 8:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. Central Clock Time, excluding United States Federal Banking Holidays. (c) "Cash-Out Price" - First of the Month price reported for the "Tennessee, Louisiana, 500 Leg" in Inside FERC's Gas Market Report. (d) "Day" - A period of 24 hours beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time. (e) "Delivery Points" - The point or points located on Transporter's System and specified in the Agreement at which Transporter shall deliver Gas on behalf of Shipper. (f) "Dekatherm" or "Dth" - One MMBtu and shall be the standard unit for purposes of nominations, scheduling, confirmations, allocations, invoicing, and balancing. (g) "Electronic" or "electronically" - Data communication between Transporter and Shipper or vice versa through Transporter's Internet Home Page or via EDI. (h) "Equivalent Thermal Quantity" - During any given period of time, the quantity of Gas measured in Dths received by Transporter at the Receipt Points equal to thermal equivalent of the quantities of Gas measured in Dths for delivery at the Delivery Points less L&U. (i) "FERC" - The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor federal agency having jurisdiction over the rates and charges assessed by Transporter under 18 CFR Sections 284.123(b)(2) and 284.224(e) of the FERC regulations, as such may be amended from time to time. (j) "Firm Service" -- Transportation Service that has the highest priority of Transportation Service offered by Transporter, as set forth herein, and shall have the priority as specified in Section 12 hereof. (k) "Gas" or "Natural Gas" - Gas produced from gas wells and oil wells and the residue gas remaining after processing such gas for the removal of liquefiable hydrocarbons therefrom. (l) "Internet Home Page" - Transporter' internet home page: www.hienergy.com (m) "Interruptible Service" - Transportation Service or Park and Loan Service that is subject to interruption by Transporter, without liability on the part of Transporter, as set forth herein, and shall have the priority as specified in Section 12 hereof. (n) "L&U" - The amount of Gas, expressed as a percentage of the Gas received by Transporter at the Receipt Points, that Transporter shall retain for lost and unaccounted-for quantities of Gas. (o) "Mcf" - One thousand (1,000) standard cubic feet of gas. "MMcf" shall mean one million (1,000,000) standard cubic feet of gas. (p) "MDQ" - Maximum daily quantity in dekatherms stated in Shipper's Agreement. (q) "Month" - A period beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first Day of a calendar month and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first Day of the next succeeding calendar month. (r) "Overrun" - Any quantity in excess of Shipper's MDQ as set forth in the Agreement. "Authorized Overrun" means an Overrun that is nominated by Shipper and approved and scheduled by Transporter. "Unauthorized Overrun" means an Overrun that Transporter does not schedule for service. (s) "Park and Loan Service" - An Interruptible Service described in Section 19 hereof provided at Transaction Points pursuant to Subpart G of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations. (t) "Party" or "Parties" - Transporter or Shipper individually or Transporter and Shipper jointly. (u) "Quality Specifications" - The quality specifications for gas received at the Receipt Points set forth in Section 16 hereof. (v) "Receipt Points" - The point or points located on the Transporter's System and specified in the Agreement at which Transporter shall receive Gas from Shipper. (w) "Tender" - A communicated offer to deliver Gas at a sufficient pressure to enter the receiving party's facilities, coupled with the present ability of immediate delivery of such Gas at such pressure. (x) "Transaction Point" - The applicable point on the Transporter's System where Gas is received and delivered pursuant to a Park and Loan Agreement. (y) "Transportation" or "Transportation Service" - A forward haul, backhaul, exchange, displacement, or other method of transporting Gas pursuant to Subpart G of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations. (z) "Year" - A period of twelve consecutive Months. 3.2 Construction. (a) Additionally, terms used throughout this Statement which are capitalized shall have the definitions given to such terms as set forth above or elsewhere in this Statement. (b) The singular of a term shall also include the plural of such term and vice versa. (c) The word "includes" and its derivatives means "includes, but not limited to" and corresponding derivative meanings. The words "hereof," "herein," "hereunder," and words of similar import, when used in this Statement shall refer to this Statement as a whole and not to any particular provision of this Statement. Unless the context clearly indicates otherwise, the word "or" is not exclusive.

record_data.record_plain_text: BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 5-Section 4 (Applicability and Character of Service) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022 4. APPLICABILITY AND CHARACTER OF TRANSPORTATION SERVICE 4.1 Applicability. This Statement shall apply to all Firm Transportation Service and Interruptible Transportation Service rendered by Transporter for Shipper pursuant to Part 284 of the FERC's regulations and the Transportation Agreement for service under this Statement. 4.2 Character of Transportation Service. Subject to the Force Majeure provisions set forth in Section 18 hereof, Transportation Service under this Statement shall consist of: (a) The receipt of Gas on behalf of Shipper at the Receipt Points or Transaction Point specified in the Transportation Agreement; (b) The Firm or Interruptible Transportation of Gas through Transporter's System; and (c) The delivery of an Equivalent Thermal Quantity of Gas by Transporter to Shipper or for Shipper's account at the Delivery Points or Transaction Point specified in the Transportation Agreement. 4.3 Subject to Laws. Transporter's Transportation Service is subject to all present and future valid laws and lawful rules, regulations, and orders of all regulatory authorities now or hereafter having jurisdiction over the services or facilities used to provide such services. The Parties acknowledge that Transportation under this Statement is subject to the provisions of Subpart G of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations ("Subpart G Regulations"). Shipper warrants that at all times during the term of the Transportation Agreement, Shipper will commit no action or omission that will cause the Transportation Service provided to Shipper to fail to comply with all applicable rules and regulations of the applicable regulatory agencies, including, without limitation, the "on behalf of" provisions of the Part 284 regulations. 4.4 Required Information. Upon request, Shipper must furnish to Transporter all information that is required for Transporter to comply with any reporting requirements of the FERC or any other duly constituted authorities. 4.5 Laws and Regulations. The Transportation Agreement is expressly made subject to this Statement, as such may be amended from time to time by Transporter and approved by any federal or state regulatory body. Transporter will have the right to propose to the FERC or other governing regulatory body such changes in its rates and this Statement at any times as it deems necessary; and the Transportation Agreement will be deemed to include any changes that are made effective pursuant to any order, regulation, or provisions of law, without prejudice to Shipper's right to protest the same. In the event of a conflict between this Statement or the Subpart G Regulations and the Transportation Agreement, the terms of this Statement and the Subpart G Regulations shall govern. If, by decree, law, order, or otherwise, any regulatory body having or asserting jurisdiction over the Transportation Agreement subjects Transporter's System or Transporter's service hereunder or thereunder to any greater or different regulation or jurisdiction than that existing on the effective date of an Transportation Agreement, notwithstanding anything in this Statement or the Transportation Agreement to the contrary, Transporter may terminate the Transportation Agreement without any further obligations or liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with such termination. If any order or regulation of a regulatory body having jurisdiction over the Transportation Agreement prohibits Transporter from charging or collecting rates specified in the Transportation Agreement, Shipper and Transporter shall negotiate in good faith to amend and restate the Transportation Agreement so as to (i) conform to the applicable order or regulation affecting such rates and (ii) to maintain the total consideration initially agreed upon by Transporter and Shipper, to the maximum extent possible; provided that, upon no less than thirty (30) days prior written notice to Shipper, Transporter shall have the right to terminate the Transportation Agreement without any further liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with such termination if Shipper and Transporter are unable to mutually agree to amend and restate the Transportation Agreement to accomplish the foregoing objectives.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 6-Section 5 (Requests for Transportation and Creditworthiness) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
5. REQUESTS FOR SERVICE AND CREDITWORTHINESS. 5.1 Requests for Transportation or Park and Loan Service. Requests for Transportation or Park and Loan Service hereunder shall be considered acceptable only if the following information is provided in writing to the Transporter at the following address: BBT Bamagas Intrastate, LLC 1501 McKinney Street Suite 800 Houston, TX 77010 Attention: Commercial Operations e-mail: legal@blackbearllc.com; contracts@lighthouseserv.com (a) Shipper's complete legal name, contact information, and use of Gas (e.g., system supply, end user); (b) In addition, Shipper shall provide the following information: (i) Projected daily quantities and total quantity to be transported by Transporter during the requested term of service; and, (ii) Receipt Points and Delivery Points and the MDQ to be received by Transporter by Receipt Point and corresponding MDQ to be delivered to Shipper by Delivery Point or, for Park and Loan Service, the Transaction Points and associated MDQ for each Transaction Point. (iii) Names of entity or entities who will deliver Gas to Transporter and entity or entities who will receive Gas from Transporter; (iv) Term of service, including (A) the date service is requested to commence, and (B) the date service is requested to terminate; and, (v) Certification that Shipper has good title to all Gas or the good right to deliver all Gas to be transported in accordance with Section 10 hereof and has entered into or will enter into all necessary arrangements to ensure that all upstream and downstream transportation will be in place prior to commencement of service. 5.2 Creditworthiness. Shipper shall provide Transporter sufficient information to determine Shipper's creditworthiness. To enable Transporter to conduct such credit appraisal, potential shipper shall submit the information set out below in Section 5.3 hereof; provided, however, that submission of such material shall not be deemed acceptance of a request for service by Transporter, which determination shall be made by Transporter only after submission of the material and information set forth below and a determination by Transporter that potential shipper is sufficiently creditworthy. Transporter shall apply consistent evaluation practices on a not unduly discriminatory basis to determine creditworthiness. 5.3 Information to be Submitted. A potential shipper may be required by Transporter to provide (a) a copy of its most recent financial statements for the period subsequent to its most recent twelve month financial statement of 10-K form, if applicable; (b) its most recent twelve month financial statement of 10-K form, if applicable; (c) bank references, (d) at least three (3) trade references which indicate that potential shipper's obligations are being paid on a prompt basis, or (e) a list of Buyer's affiliates including parent and subsidiaries. If Shipper cannot provide the information required by (a) or (b) above, if applicable, Shipper shall provide such information for its parent company. Such documents shall be provided to Transporter at the address shown above. 5.4 Other Information. Prior to or at the time that Shipper returns the executed Transportation Agreement to Transporter, Shipper shall provide the following information to Transporter in writing at the address set forth in the Transportation Agreement: (a) Unless Shipper is a local distribution company, interstate pipeline, or intrastate pipeline and Shipper is using such Gas for its system supply, the name of the corporate entities receiving the Gas to be transported under this Statement; (b) Verification that the entities in subsection (a) above have entered into the necessary contractual arrangements with Shipper or others to purchase the Gas; and (c) Such other information as Transporter, in its sole judgement reasonably exercised, requires in order to process Shipper's request for Transportation. 5.5 Further Assurances. (a) Transporter shall not be required to perform Transportation Service or to continue to perform Transportation Service under this Statement or any Transportation Agreement with Shipper if Shipper is or has become insolvent or, at Transporter's request, fails to demonstrate creditworthiness or fails to make payments when due pursuant to Section 15.7 of this Statement; (b) Notwithstanding Section 5.5(a) herein, Shipper may receive Transportation Service under this Statement if Shipper either (i) prepays equal to three (3) Months of the Monthly Demand Rate under its Firm Service Agreements or prepays for three (3) Months of service under its Interruptible Service Agreements or Park and Loan Service Agreements, as applicable, based on the revenues Transporter would receive if Transporter was performing such Transportation Service at the greater of the rate of Shipper's prior levels of service or Shipper's nominations made pursuant to Section 8 of this Statement or (ii) furnishes within ten (10) days of notice by Transporter good and sufficient security, as determined solely by Transporter, of a continuing nature equal to three (3) Months of the Monthly Demand Rate under its Firm Service Agreements or prepays for three (3) Months of service under its Interruptible Service Agreements or Park and Loan Service Agreements, as applicable, based on the revenues Transporter would receive if Transporter was performing such Transportation Service at the greater of the rate of Shipper's prior levels of service or Shipper's nominations made pursuant to Section 8 of this Statement. (c) In the event Shipper that is not creditworthy neither prepays the required revenues equal to three (3) Months nor furnishes the required security, Transporter may, without waiving any additional rights or remedies it may have, suspend further Transportation Service until such prepayment or security is received. (d) For purposes of this Statement, the insolvency of Shipper shall be evidenced by the filing by Shipper or any parent entity thereof of a voluntary petition in bankruptcy or the entry of a decree or order by a court having jurisdiction in the premises adjudging the Shipper or any parent entity thereof a bankrupt or insolvent, or approving as properly filed a petition seeking reorganization, arrangement, adjustment or composition of or in respect of the Shipper or any parent entity thereof under the Federal Bankruptcy Act or any other applicable federal or state law, or appointing a receiver, liquidator, assignee, trustee, sequestrator (or other similar official) of the Shipper or any parent entity thereof or of any substantial part of its property, or the ordering of the winding-up or liquidation of its affairs, with said order or decree continuing unstayed and in effect for a period of sixty (60) consecutive days. 5.6 Termination. Requests for Transportation Service hereunder shall be void unless Shipper executes and returns an executed Transportation Agreement for service under this Statement within thirty (30) days after Transporter has delivered the applicable Transportation Agreement to Shipper.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 7-Section 6 (Rates and Charges) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022 6. RATES AND CHARGES 6.1 Rates. Rates for service herein are provided pursuant to Section 284.123(b)(2) of the FERC's regulations. Unless Transporter and Shipper agree in writing to a lower rate for a specified period of time, for Firm or Interruptible Transportation (including Park and Loan Service) under this Statement and the Transportation Agreement, the charge for service shall be the maximum rate per MMBTU approved by the FERC. The charges for Firm Transportation Service shall be the lesser of either the maximum rate approved by the FERC or the rate set out in the Firm Service Agreement multiplied each Month or Day, as applicable, by the MDQ in the Firm Transportation Agreement. The charge for Interruptible Transportation Service shall be the lesser of either the maximum rate approved by the FERC or the rate set out in the Interruptible Service Agreement multiplied by the quantities of Gas received by Transporter pursuant to the Interruptible Transportation Agreement. The charges for Park and Loan Service shall be the lesser of either the maximum rate approved by the FERC or the rate set out in the Park and Loan Service Agreement multiplied each Day by the amount in Shipper's PAL Account. 6.2 L&U. For all Gas received by Transporter at any Receipt Point, Transporter shall retain the L&U based on the BTUs of the Gas received at the Receipt Points. 6.3 Regulatory Fees. In addition to the other applicable charges pursuant to this Section 6, Shipper shall pay or reimburse Transporter for all regulatory fees and charges that Transporter is assessed (i) by the FERC or any other governmental authority having jurisdiction and (ii) as a result of Shipper's request for service under this Statement. 6.4 New Facilities. Transporter shall have no obligation to install any new or additional facilities to provide Transportation Service for any person requesting service. Unless otherwise mutually agreed to by Transporter and Shipper, in addition to the other applicable charges pursuant to this Section 6, Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for the costs and expenses incurred by Transporter associated with any new or additional facilities (including any costs or expenses associated with reestablishing existing facilities and any tax gross-up) which Transporter has agreed to install and are necessary to receive, measure, transport, or deliver Gas to or for the account of Shipper or to ensure that the Gas Quality Specifications are met. Any such facilities shall be designed, owned, and operated by Transporter. 6.5 Third Party Fees. In addition to the other applicable charges pursuant to this Section 6, Shipper shall pay any and all transportation, measurement, testing, compression, or other fees or charges imposed by any third party on deliveries at any Receipt Point or Delivery Point. Notwithstanding the foregoing, unless otherwise agreed upon in writing, in the event Transporter pays any such fees and charges, Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any such fees or charges paid by Transporter with respect to Shipper's Gas. With regard to Shipper's Gas, in the event that Transporter incurs any costs or expenses as the result of any governmental requirement to pay for, trade for, or otherwise minimize or mitigate greenhouse gasses (including, but not limited to CO2 and methane) attributable to or as a result of any activity of or by Transporter hereunder, Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for its pro-rata share of any costs or expenses associated therewith. 6.6 Taxes. In addition to the charges pursuant to this Section 6, upon billing, Shipper will reimburse Transporter for all taxes levied upon and paid by Transporter with respect to the Gas delivered to Transporter hereunder. Such taxes will include licenses, fees, greenhouse gas and other charges levied, assessed, or made by any governmental authority on the act, right, or privilege of transporting, handling, or delivering Gas which are measured by the volume, heat content, value, or sales price of the Gas or the rates and charges of Transporter hereunder. Such taxes will not include ad valorem, capital stock, income, or excess profit, general franchise taxes imposed on corporations on account of their corporate existence or on their right to do business within the state as a foreign corporation, and similar taxes. 6.7 Payment. Shipper shall pay or reimburse Transporter for the costs, expenses, fees, and charges pursuant to this Section 6 in accordance with the Section 15 hereof.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 8-Section 7 (Receipt and Delivery Points) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022 7. RECEIPT, DELIVERY AND TRANSACTION POINTS 7.1 Receipt Points. The Receipt Points at which Transporter shall receive Gas for Transportation under this Statement shall be set forth in the Transportation Agreement. Prior to execution of the Transportation Agreement, Transporter and Shipper shall mutually agree upon an initial MDQ for each Receipt Point. Such initial MDQ shall be no greater than the lesser of (i) the physical limits of such Receipt Point or (ii) the quantity of Gas Shipper can demonstrate is currently available to Shipper for Transportation from such Receipt Points to such Delivery Points designated by Shipper less L&U. The Transportation Agreement will state the MDQ at each Receipt Point. Such MDQ may be amended by mutual agreement between Transporter and Shipper, whereupon Transporter will revise Receipt Point exhibit to the Transportation Agreement accordingly and provide Shipper with a copy of such revised exhibit. 7.2 Adding or Deleting Receipt Points. Subject to Section 6.4 hereof with regard to reimbursement for facilities, Receipt Points may be added or deleted by Shipper from time to time. In the event Shipper wishes to add Receipt Points to the Transportation Agreement, it must submit a request pursuant to Section 5 hereof. As between Shipper and Transporter, such request shall become effective after it has been accepted and fully processed by Transporter, and Transporter has provided Shipper with a revised Receipt Point exhibit to the Transportation Agreement. 7.3 Delivery Points. The Delivery Points at which Transporter shall deliver Gas hereunder shall be set forth in the Transportation Agreement. Prior to execution of the Transportation Agreement, Transporter and Shipper shall mutually agree upon an initial MDQ for each Delivery Point. For each Delivery Point, the initial MDQ shall be no greater than the lesser of (i) the physical limits of such Delivery Point or (ii) the quantity of Gas Shipper can demonstrate is currently available to Shipper for Transportation to such Delivery Points. The MDQ for all Delivery Points shall be no greater than the sum of the MDQs for the Receipt Points less L&U. 7.4 Adding or Deleting Delivery Points. Subject to Section 6.4 hereof with regard to reimbursement for facilities, Delivery Points may be added or deleted by Shipper from time to time. In the event Shipper wishes to add Delivery Points to the Transportation Agreement, it must submit a request pursuant to Section 5 hereof. As between Shipper and Transporter, such request shall become effective after it has been accepted and fully processed by Transporter and Transporter has provided Shipper with a revised Delivery Point exhibit to the Transportation Agreement. 7.5 Transaction Point. The Transaction Point at which Transporter shall be an existing Receipt Point or Delivery Point on Transporter's System where Transporter will receive or deliver Gas shall be set forth in the Transportation Agreement. Prior to execution of the Transportation Agreement, Transporter and Shipper shall mutually agree upon an initial MDQ for each Transaction Point. For each Transaction Point, the initial MDQ shall be no greater than the lesser of (i) the physical limits of such Transaction Point or (ii) the quantity of Gas Shipper can demonstrate is currently available to Shipper for Parking and Loan Service at Transaction Point less L&U. 7.6 Receipt Point Pressure. Shipper (or its designee) will deliver Gas to Transporter at the Receipt Points at pressures sufficient to enter Transporter's System at such points; provided, however, that Shipper's delivery pressure into Transporter's System at the Receipt Points may not cause the pressure to exceed Transporter's maximum allowable operating pressure at any such point. 7.7 Delivery Point Pressure. Transporter will deliver Gas to Shipper or Shipper's designee at the pressure then prevailing at each of the Delivery Points to the extent that the delivery pressure from the interconnecting pipelines upstream of Transporter's System deliver gas to Transporter is sufficient for Transporter to maintain such pressure at the Delivery Points. 7.8 Transaction Point Pressure. Shipper (or its designee) will deliver Gas to Transporter at a Transaction Point at pressures sufficient to enter Transporter's System at such points; provided, however, that Shipper's delivery pressure into Transporter's System at the Receipt Points may not cause the pressure to exceed Transporter's maximum allowable operating pressure at any such point. Transporter will deliver Gas to Shipper or Shipper's designee at the pressure then prevailing at each Transaction Point to the extent that the delivery pressure from the interconnecting pipelines upstream of Transporter's System deliver gas to Transporter is sufficient for Transporter to maintain such pressure at the Transaction Point. 7.9 No Pressure Obligation. Unless otherwise separately agreed to by Transporter and Shipper, Transporter shall have no obligation to alter its pipeline pressures, provide compression, or modify its pipeline operations in order to effectuate the receipt or delivery of Gas.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 9-Section 8 (Nominations, Balancing, Cash-Out, and Penalties) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
8. NOMINATIONS, BALANCING, CASH-OUT, AND PENALTIES 8.1 Monthly Transportation Nomination Procedure. Transporter and Shipper shall adhere to the following monthly nomination procedures: (a) Within five (5) Business Days prior to the beginning of the Month, Shipper or its representative shall submit via Transporter's Internet Home Page to Transporter Shipper's best estimate of its daily requirements for Transportation from each of the Receipt Points and to each of the Delivery Points for the following Month. Such estimates shall be stated in Dekatherms. (b) Nomination quantities for each Receipt Point and Delivery Point (including Transaction Points) shall be referred to herein as the "Receipt Point Nominated Quantities" and "Delivery Point Nominated Quantities," respectively. Transporter shall provide notification to each Shipper or its representative of any changes to the nomination quantity as a result of the scheduling process for each nomination cycle. (c) Once nominated by Shipper for the Month, Shipper may change the nomination quantity at any Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or Transaction Point by submitting a revised nomination quantity no later than 11:30 a.m. Central Time on the Business Day prior to the Day such revised quantity is to be effective. (d) Shipper shall make any necessary arrangements, including nominations, with other parties to be able to deliver the Receipt Point Nominated Quantities to Transporter at the Receipt Points or Transaction Points. Such arrangements shall be compatible with Transporter's System operations and shall provide for coordinated dispatching with Transporter. (e) Shipper shall make any necessary arrangements for downstream transportation from the Delivery Points or Transaction Points to enable Transporter to make deliveries for the account of Shipper at the Delivery Points. Such arrangements shall be compatible with Transporter's System operations and shall provide for coordinated dispatching with Transporter. Such arrangements shall include, but shall not be limited to, Shipper's nomination of the Delivery Point Nominated Quantities for transportation on the downstream Transporter's System. (f) Transporter shall not be obligated to receive (1) at any Receipt Point or Transaction Point a quantity of Gas different than the Receipt Point Nominated Quantities, or (2) from all Receipt Points an Equivalent Thermal Quantity of Gas (plus L&U) different than the quantity of Gas nominated by Shipper or its representative at the Delivery Points. Transporter shall not be obligated to deliver at any Delivery Point or Transaction Point a quantity of Gas different than the Delivery Point Nominated Quantities. Furthermore, in the event the downstream transporter at the Delivery Points fails or refuses to take delivery of any quantity of Gas from Transporter for any reason, Transporter shall not be obligated to receive the corresponding quantity (plus L&U) of Gas from Shipper at the Receipt Points. (g) To the extent not incompatible with operation of Transporter's System and its scheduling capabilities, Transporter shall accommodate nomination changes by Shipper. 8.2 Transportation Balancing and Cash-Out. (a) Due to Transporter's need to allocate unused capacity to Interruptible shippers in an efficient and systematic manner, Shipper may be required to balance, on a daily, monthly, or other basis, its nominations with its actual deliveries of Gas to Transporter at the Receipt Points. (b) Shipper and Transporter also intend that the quantity of Gas scheduled for receipt each Day at the Receipt Points will be Equivalent Thermal Quantity of Gas scheduled for delivery to Shipper at the Delivery Points plus L&U. Any imbalance created when the actual physical quantity of Gas at the Receipt Points (less L&U) is different than the actual quantity of Gas allocated to Shipper at the Delivery Points will be the "Operational Imbalance," which will be the responsibility of the Shipper. (c) The best available operating flow data at the Receipt Points and the Delivery Points shall be used during any period to determine the estimated Operational Imbalance with physical or nominated quantity adjustments to be made during the current period to attempt to maintain or achieve an Operational Imbalance of zero. (d) Associated with each Operational Imbalance at the end of each Month shall be a percentage which shall be calculated by dividing (i) the quantities of Gas received by Transporter from Shipper at the Receipt Points (less L&U) by (ii) the quantity of Gas delivered by Transporter to or for Shipper at the Delivery Points. The Operational Imbalance will be cashed out by multiplying the Operational Imbalance expressed in MMBTUs by the percentage ("Cash-Out Percentage") corresponding to the percentage associated with the Operational Imbalance and then multiplying the product by the posted Cash-Out Price for the Month during which such receipts and deliveries of Gas occurred. If the Operational Imbalance is greater than 100%, payment will be made by Transporter to Shipper. If the Operational Imbalance is less than 100%, payment will be made by Shipper to Transporter. Operational Imbalance: Cash-Out Percentage: (Receipts/Deliveries)
100 to 105% 100% of Cash-Out Price 105% to 110% 85% of Cash-Out Price 110% to 115% 75% of Cash-Out Price 115% to 120% 60% of Cash-Out Price 120% 50% of Cash-Out Price
100% N/A
100 to 95% 100% of Cash-Out Price 95 to 90% 115% of Cash-Out Price 90 to 85% 125% of Cash-Out Price 85 to 70% 140% of Cash-Out Price 70% 150% of Cash-Out Price Which price shall be adjusted to include any transportation or other charges associated with the upstream pipelines.
(e) In the event that Inside FERC Gas Market Report ceases to publish the Cash-Out Price or ceases publication in its entirety, Transporter will substitute a comparable index upon which to base the Cash-Out Price. Such substitute index shall reflect the spot market price of Gas in the producing area in which the Gas transported under the Transportation Agreement is located. (f) If Transporter determines in its sole discretion that due to operational constraints or otherwise it cannot reasonably enforce any or all of the provisions of Sections 8.2(a), 8.2(b), 8.2(c), 8.2(d), or 8.2(e) hereof, it may in its sole discretion waive any or all of such provisions. Any such waiver shall be applied on a not unduly discriminatory basis. (g) An event of Force Majeure, as defined in Section 18 hereof, shall not excuse Shipper from the operation of the provisions of Sections 8.2(a), 8.2(b), 8.2(c), 8.2(d), or 8.2(e) hereof inasmuch as Shipper can control its imbalances by adjusting its actual deliveries to Transporter at the Receipt Point or its Delivery Point Nominated Quantities. 8.3 Billing and Payment. Billing and payment of the cash-out and applicable penalties described above shall be pursuant to Section 15 hereof.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 10-Section 9 (Possession of Gas) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022 9. POSSESSION OF GAS 9.1 Possession and Control. As between Transporter and Shipper: (a) Shipper shall be deemed to be in control and possession of the Gas transported pursuant to the Transportation Agreement prior to delivery thereof to Transporter at the Receipt Points or Transaction Points and after delivery thereof by Transporter at the Delivery Points or Transaction Points; and (b) Transporter shall be deemed to be in control and possession of such Gas after delivery thereof by Shipper at the Receipt Points or Transaction Points and until redelivery thereof by Transporter at the Delivery Points or Transaction Points. 9.2 Liability. Except for Gas not meeting the Quality Specifications, the Party in control and possession of the Gas shall be responsible for and shall indemnify and hold the other Party harmless from and against any losses, injuries, claims, liabilities, damages, and expenses caused thereby and occurring while the Gas is in the possession of the Party in control, except to the extent of the fault of the other Party. If Shipper delivers Gas that does not meet the Quality Specifications, Shipper shall be liable to and shall indemnify and hold Transporter and any third party harmless from and against any losses, injuries, claims, liabilities, or damages resulting therefrom. 9.3 Notwithstanding any other provision, each Party shall release and Indemnify the other Party from indirect, special, punitive, exemplary, or consequential damages or losses including damages or losses for lost production, lost revenue, lost product, lost profits, lost business, or business interruptions that the indemnifying Party suffers in relation to any service Agreement, provided this does not apply to claims for which a Party, as indemnitee, is owed indemnification by the other Party, as indemnitor, under the indemnity provisions herein.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 11-Section 10 (Warranty of Title to Gas) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022 10. WARRANTY OF TITLE TO GAS 10.1 Shipper Warranty. Shipper warrants that it has good title to all the Gas delivered by it to Transporter or the right to deliver such Gas to Transporter under the Transportation Agreement and this Statement, and that such Gas shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances, and claims whatsoever. Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold Transporter harmless from and against all losses, costs, suits, actions, damages, and expenses incurred by it on account of any such liens, encumbrances, and claims. 10.2 Transporter Warranty. Transporter warrants that at the time of delivery to or for the account of Shipper, the Gas delivered hereunder shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances, and claims whatsoever resulting from Transporter's possession or Transportation of the Gas pursuant to the Transportation Agreement and this Statement, and agrees to indemnify and hold Shipper harmless from and against all losses, costs, suits, actions, damages, and expenses incurred by it on account of any such liens, encumbrances, and claims whatsoever.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 12-Section 11 (Determination of Deliveries) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
11. DETERMINATION OF DELIVERIES 11.1 Allocation. Subject to Section 12 of this Statement, in the event Gas tendered by Shipper to Transporter for Transportation is delivered with Gas of other Shippers through the same meter at any Receipt Point, Transporter will allocate quantities received at such point among Shipper and such other Shippers on a daily basis in direct proportion to each Shipper's confirmed Receipt Point Nominated Quantities, as such term is defined in Section 8.1 hereof. 11.2 Commingling. Gas transported for Shipper shall be commingled with Gas of other Shippers at a Delivery Point. The quantities of Gas delivered for each Shipper's account at such point shall be based on the total quantities, less L&U, received from each Shipper at the Receipt Points.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 13-Section 12 (Priority of Service) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (2.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022 12. PRIORITY OF SERVICE 12.1 Priority of Service. Service shall be curtailed in the following priority based upon class of service with "(a)" being the lowest class of service. The next higher class of service shall not be curtailed until all quantities of lower classes of service have been curtailed: (a) Make up gas; (b) Park and Loan Service and Interruptible Service; (c) Firm Transportation Service other than that described in Section 12.1(d) below. (d) The following Firm Transportation Agreements pursuant to which Transporter is obligated to transport up to 138,000 MMBTU per day under each contract except for interruptions or curtailments by reason of (A) the express consent of Calpine Energy Services, L.P. or its successors ("Calpine") or Decatur Energy Center, LLC or its successors ("DEC"), as the case may be, (B) force majeure, (C) applicable laws, rules or regulations, or (D) failure by either Calpine or DEC, as the case may be, (i) to deliver sufficient gas quantities to enable Transporter to deliver equivalent quantities at the delivery points, (ii) to deliver gas at a pressure sufficient to permit Transporter to redeliver the gas at a pressure greater than 500 psig, (iii) to deliver gas meeting the quality specifications, or (iv) to deliver gas quantities at a rate of flow which would enable Transporter to redeliver the gas at the flow rates set out in the terms of the Firm Transportation Agreements: (i) That certain Firm Transportation Agreement (FT0005) dated June 28, 2000 by and between Transporter and Calpine for the transportation of natural gas from the interconnection between the Transporter and Tennessee Gas Pipeline Company located in or near Section 2, Township 4 South, Range 13 West, of Colbert County, Alabama, from the interconnection between the Transporter and Texas Eastern Transmission Company seated in or near Section 8, Township 4 South, Range 12 West, of Colbert County, Alabama, and from the interconnection between Transporter and AlaTenn, LLC located in Morgan County, Alabama to the interconnection of Transporter and Calpine in Section 4, Township 5 South, Range 5 West, Morgan County, Alabama (Morgan Energy Center). (ii) That certain Firm Transportation Agreement (FT0004) dated June 28, 2000 by and between Transporter and DEC for the transportation of natural gas from the interconnection between the Transporter and Tennessee Gas Pipeline Company located in or near Section 2, Township 4 South, Range 13 West, of Colbert County, Alabama, from the interconnection between the Transporter and Texas Eastern Transmission Company seated in or near Section 8, Township 4 South, Range 12 West, of Colbert County, Alabama, and from the interconnection between Transporter and AlaTenn, LLC located in Morgan County, Alabama to the interconnection of Transporter and Calpine in Section 11, Township 5 South, Range 5 West, Morgan County, Alabama (Decatur Energy Center). 12.2 Capacity Allocation. (a) In allocating capacity for and scheduling service under Section 12.1(a)-(c) hereof, Transporter may give priority based on: (i) The rates which shippers are paying, with a shipper paying a greater rate being given priority over a shipper paying a lesser rate; and (ii) A shipper's willingness to pay a higher unit rate for such service (not to exceed the maximum approved rate for such service) with shippers willing to pay the highest unit rate receiving first priority and so on (with priority among shippers willing to pay the same unit rate for such service determined as set forth in Section 12.2(a)-(c) hereof). (b) In allocating capacity for and scheduling service under Section 12.1(a)-(c) hereof for shippers paying the same rate, Transporter shall allocate the available capacity within that service category on a pro rata basis. (c) In allocating capacity for and scheduling service under Section 12.1(d) hereof, Transporter shall allocate available capacity according to the terms of the Firm Transportation Agreements described in Sections 12.1(d)(i). 12.3 Curtailment. On any Day, Transporter may curtail or interrupt deliveries in accordance with the priorities set forth in this Section 12 to the extent necessary to maintain the priority of services set forth above. After determining Shipper's priority of service within a service category, Transporter shall curtail services to Shipper based upon the daily scheduled volumes of Shipper and other shippers receiving the same priority of service within that service category; provided however, such scheduled volumes shall not exceed (i) a Transporter's then-current capability to deliver such shipper's Gas, (ii) the available capacity of Transporter's System, (iii) the capacity on any applicable segment of Transporter's System, or (iv) the capacity at any applicable Receipt Points or Delivery Points.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 14-Section 13 (Other Conditions of Service) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
13. OTHER CONDITIONS OF SERVICE 13.1 Minimum Delivery Volume. Provided that Transporter terminates or suspends service to similarly-situated Interruptible Transportation Service shippers on a not unduly discriminatory basis, if Shipper nominates or delivers an average of less than one hundred (100) Dths per Day during any Month ("Minimum Delivery Volume") at any Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or Transaction Point under any Interruptible Transportation agreement, Transporter shall have the right: (a) To refuse to provide service or to suspend service at any such Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or Transaction Point during that Month; or (b) Upon thirty (30) days written notice to Shipper, to terminate the Transportation Agreement with regard to any such Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or Transaction Point. If Transporter refuses to provide or suspends service or if Transporter terminates the Transportation Agreement with regard to any such Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or Transaction Point, Transporter shall be deemed released from all obligations and liabilities concerning the receipt or delivery of Gas at such Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or Transaction Point under the Transportation Agreement upon effective date of the suspension or termination of such service; provided, however, that Transporter's right to terminate shall not apply if: (i) Shipper notifies Transporter in advance that Shipper does not wish to obtain service during the Month or at any Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or Transaction Point the Minimum Delivery Volume will not be nominated, received, or delivered; or (ii) The inability to receive or deliver the Minimum Delivery Volume is due to an interruption of service by Transporter. 13.2 Suspension of Deliveries. If within three (3) Months after the execution of an Interruptible Transportation Agreement, Shipper has not commenced service under the provisions of such Agreement or, if Shipper has commenced service but fails to use service for a Year after commencement, Transporter may, on a not unduly discriminatory basis, terminate the Transportation Agreement and Shipper's request for Interruptible Service shall be deemed a nullity for all present and future purposes. Transporter shall give Shipper written notice thirty (30) days in advance of termination of the Transportation Agreement. Shipper may retain the Transportation Agreement by notifying Transporter in writing of its intent to retain the Transportation Agreement; provided, however, if Shipper fails to use Interruptible Service for a Year after notice of its intent to retain such service, the Transportation Agreement and Shipper's request for Interruptible Service shall be automatically terminated.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 15-Section 14 (Operational Requirements and Assessments by Upstream or Downstream Pipelines) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
14. OPERATIONAL REQUIREMENTS AND ASSESSMENTS BY UPSTREAM OR DOWNSTREAM PIPELINES 14.1 Operational Order. Transporter shall have the right, in its sole discretion, to issue an Operational Flow Order ("OFO") on Transporter's System when operational conditions warrant, an upstream or downstream pipeline has instituted an Operational Flow Order, or other conditions exist that affect the integrity of Transporter's System or jeopardize Firm Service. If Shipper fails to comply with the OFO after notice by either phone or email, Shipper shall pay a penalty equal to $15.00 plus the Cash-out Price defined in Section 8.2(d) hereof for each MMBTU of Gas that deviates from the OFO. For purposes of this Section 14.1, an OFO is an order issued to alleviate conditions that threaten the safety or integrity of Transporter's System or an upstream or downstream pipeline system. In the event of an extreme condition requiring an immediate response, Transporter may take such unilateral actions as it deems reasonably necessary, and Shipper shall indemnify and hold Transporter harmless against any losses, injuries, claims, liabilities, or damages resulting therefrom. 14.2 Third-Party Penalties. Transporter shall have the right, in its sole discretion, to charge Shipper for any charges or penalties assessed Transporter by an upstream or downstream pipeline to the extent that Shipper's actions caused the assessment of the charges or penalties.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 16-Section 15 (Billing and Payment) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
15. BILLING AND PAYMENT 15.1 Statement and Payment. On or before the 15th day of each Month, Transporter shall render to Shipper a statement setting forth the amount due, deductions made, total quantity, and BTU content of Gas received during the previous Month at the Receipt Points or Transaction Points and the total quantity of Gas delivered at the Delivery Points or Transaction Points during said Month, together with any balancing charges and penalties and other costs, expenses, fees, and charges owed by Shipper to Transporter pursuant to the Transportation Agreement or this Statement. Shipper shall pay Transporter in accordance with such statement the later of the twenty-fifth (25th) day of each Month or ten (10) days from the date of the invoice. Payments from Shipper to Transporter shall be made by wire transfer in immediately available funds to an account designated by Transporter. 15.2 Interest. If either Transporter or Shipper (a "Party") fails to pay the other Party any amount when due, interest thereon shall accrue at a rate equal to the rate then set forth in 18 C.F.R. Section 154.501 of the FERC's Regulations from the date payment was due until the date payment is made. 15.3 Estimates. In the event any quantities are estimated for any period, corrected statements shall be rendered by Transporter to Shipper and paid by Shipper or credited by Transporter, as the case may be, in each instance in which the actual quantity received or delivered hereunder with respect to a Month shall be determined to be at variance with the estimated quantity theretofore made the basis of billing and payment hereunder. 15.4 Error. If an error is discovered in the amount billed in any statement rendered by Transporter, then such error will be adjusted within thirty (30) days of the discovery of the error. 15.5 Disputes. If a bona fide dispute arises as to the amount payable in any statement rendered, then Shipper will nevertheless pay the undisputed amount payable to Transporter under the statement rendered pending resolution of the dispute. With regard to any amount payable in an the invoice that is disputed, the Parties will act in a diligent and good faith manner to resolve any such dispute before a Party initiates a proceeding for the formal resolution of such dispute. Upon resolution of such dispute, to the extent that Shipper owes Transporter any amount payable, Shipper will pay any monies owed Transporter, including interest calculated in accordance with Section 15.2 hereof, in accordance with the terms of this Section 15 hereof. 15.6 Audit. Each Party to the Transportation Agreement or its representative shall have the right at all reasonable times and upon reasonable prior notice to examine the books and records of the other Party to the Transportation Agreement to the extent necessary to confirm the accuracy of any statement, charge, computation, or demand made under or pursuant to the Transportation Agreement or this Statement. Any statement shall be final as to all Parties unless questioned within two (2) years after payment thereof has been made. 15.7 Failure to Pay. Except in the instance of a bona fide dispute as set forth in Section 15.5 herein, if Shipper fails to pay for services or any additional charges for thirty (30) days after such payment is due, in addition to any other remedy, Transporter may without liability, suspend further receipt and delivery of Gas until any overdue amount is paid.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 17-Section 16 (Quality Specifications) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
16. QUALITY SPECIFICATIONS 16.1 Quality Specifications. Gas delivered to Transporter at each Receipt Point under the Transportation Agreement must meet the more stringent of each of the quality specifications set forth below and, if delivered to another pipeline, each of the quality specifications of the pipeline to which Gas is delivered at each Delivery Point in accordance with each such pipeline's then current quality specifications. Transporter's Quality Specifications requires that all Gas delivered to Transporter at the each Receipt Point: (a) Objectionable Materials: The Gas shall be commercially free from dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, or other objectionable liquid or solid matter that might become separated from the Gas in the course of transmission through pipelines. (b) Free Water and Liquid Hydrocarbons: The Gas delivered to the Receipt Points after standard mechanical separation by Shipper shall be free of water and free liquid hydrocarbons. (c) Vapor: The Gas shall be free of water at the temperature and pressure at which the Gas is delivered and shall not contain any hydrocarbons that might condense to free liquids in the pipeline under normal pipeline conditions; and in no event shall the Gas contain water vapor in excess of seven (7) pounds per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet, measured at fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 p.s.i.a.) at a standard temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60 F). (d) Hydrogen Sulfide: The Gas shall not contain more than one-quarter (1/4) grains of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) standard cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the Parties. (e) Total Sulfur: The Gas shall not contain more than ten (10) grains of total sulfur per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the Parties. (f) Total Inerts (Carbon Dioxide and Nitrogen): The Gas shall not contain more than four percent (4%) by volume of a combined total of carbon dioxide (CO2) and nitrogen (N2). (g) Oxygen: The Gas shall not contain more than 0.005 mole percent of oxygen (O2). (h) Temperature: The Gas shall have a temperature of not less than forty degrees Fahrenheit (40o F) or more than one hundred and twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120o F). (i) Gross Heating Value: The Gas shall contain a daily average heating content of not less than nine hundred sixty-seven (967) Btu's per cubic foot at 14.73 p.s.i.a. dry. (j) Liquid Hydrocarbons: The Gas shall not contain more than two-tenths (0.2) of a gallon of natural gasoline in a liquefiable state. 16.2 Receipt Point Non-Conformity. Should Shipper's Gas at any Receipt Point not comply with the Quality Specifications, Transporter shall immediately have the right to discontinue Transportation of Gas from such Receipt Point and shall notify Shipper in writing of the Quality Specifications violation. Within forty-eight (48) hours thereafter, Shipper will be required to submit to Transporter a plan to conform such Gas to the Quality Specifications. If Shipper does not submit a plan and Shipper desires to continue to flow non-specification Gas, Transporter shall have the right, at its sole discretion, but not the obligation, to accept said non-specification Gas, provided that Transporter shall have the right to cease taking such non-specification Gas at any time or from time to time. If Shipper does not conform the non-specification Gas to the Quality Specifications and if Transporter does not accept said non-specification Gas, Transporter may terminate the Transportation Agreement, without any further liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with such termination, upon thirty (30) days written notice to Shipper. 16.3 Delivery Point Non-Conformity. If Shipper tenders Gas that complies with the Quality Specifications but Transporter delivers at the Delivery Points Gas that does not comply with such Quality Specifications, Transporter will, with due diligence, take action to conform such Gas to the Quality Specifications.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 18-Section 17 (Measurement) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022
17. MEASUREMENT. 17.1 Base Conditions. (a) The unit of volume for measurement of Gas delivered shall be one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas at a base temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60o F) and at an absolute pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch, absolute (14.73 p.s.i.a). All volumes shall be measured and calculated according to the current standards prescribed in the American Gas Association Report No. 3, Orifice Metering of Natural Gas and Other Hydrocarbon Fluids, Parts 1-4, as amended from time to time or as mutually agreed upon between the Parties. (b) Adjustments to measured Gas volumes for the effects of compressibility shall be made according to the latest revision of the standard, American Gas Association (AGA), Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 8, Compressibility Factors of Natural Gas and Other Related Hydrocarbon Gases. (c) For purposes of measurement hereunder, the atmospheric pressure shall be assumed to be fourteen and four hundredths pounds per square inch, absolute (14.40 p.s.i.a.) irrespective of variations in the actual atmospheric pressure from time to time. 17.2 Recalculation. Any volume recalculation shall utilize a mutually agreeable technique to compensate for the inherent inaccuracy associated with calculating volumes from averages of the flowing parameters as opposed to the actual instantaneous values used by the original flow-computing device. 17.3 Quality Basis. (a) The total energy value of Gas delivered shall be reported in Dekatherms, as the product of volumes measured and the gross heating value determined. (b) Heating values shall be expressed in BTU's per cubic foot, determined by calculation from compositional analysis according to the Gas Processors Association (GPA) Publication 2172, Calculation of Gross Heating Value, Specific Gravity, and Compressibility of Natural Gas Mixtures from Compositional Analysis (latest revision). Heating values shall be converted to gross heating values that reflect adjustments from actual delivery conditions for temperature, pressure, water content, and compressibility. 17.4 Meters. (a) If orifice meters are used in the measurement of Gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed, and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 3, Part 2, Specification and Installation Requirements, and AGA Report No. 3, Part 3, Natural Gas Applications, latest revision. (b) If ultrasonic meters are used in the measurement of Gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed, and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 9, Measurement of Gas by Multipath Ultrasonic Meters, latest revision. (c) If turbine meters are used in the measurement of Gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 7, Measurement of Gas by Turbine Meters, latest revision (d) If rotary positive displacement meters are used in the measurement of Gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed, and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 9, Measurement of Gas by Multipath Ultrasonic Meters, latest revision. 17.5 Electronic Flow Measurement. The Electronic Flow Measurement (EFM) system shall be capable of establishing an audit trail by compiling and retaining sufficient electronic data and information for the purpose of verifying daily and hourly quantities and shall comply with the American Petroleum Institute, Manual of Petroleum Measurement Standards, Chapter 21, Section 1 - Electronic Gas Measurement (API Chapter 21.1). The Transporter shall preserve audit trail information for a minimum of five (5) years or the time required by any governmental agency, whichever is greater. 17.6 Pulsation. When gas compressors are located close to and either upstream or downstream of the meter station, a pulsation dampener shall be installed in the piping between the compressor and the meter station. If pulsation induced measurement errors are found to be 0.2%, it will be the responsibility of the Shipper to reduce the error to that level or a higher level acceptable to Transporter. 17.7 Gas Sampling. (a) Transporter will determine the specific gravity, the gross heating value, and composition of the Gas by taking a representative sample according to the schedule below. Sampling or collection shall be performed during Transporter's scheduled meter inspection and calibration test and all samples shall be obtained and analyzed using Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2261, Analysis for Natural Gas and Similar Gaseous Mixtures by Gas Chromatograph. These analytical results shall be applied at the beginning of the Month the sample was taken and until a subsequent representative sample is applied. (b) The sampling rate shall be determined on the following volumetric basis: (i) For daily average flow rates of 5000 MCFD or less, on a monthly basis, the sampling rate shall be quarterly. (ii) For average daily flow rates greater than 5000 MCFD, on a monthly basis, the sampling rate shall be monthly. (c) Samples collected by spot or continuous, proportional to flow, sampling methods shall be collected using procedures and equipment specified in Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2166, Obtaining Natural Gas Samples for Analysis by Gas Chromatography or in the American Petroleum Institute (API) Manual of Petroleum Measurement Standards (MPMS), Chapter 14, Section 1, Collecting and Handling of Natural Gas Samples for Custody Transfer, latest revisions. (d) When a gas chromatograph is used to determine the real-time Hexanes plus quantity, the applicable physical properties required for the characterization of the Hexanes plus quantity shall be determined using an extended analysis as detailed in Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2261, Analysis for Natural Gas and Similar Gaseous Mixtures by Gas Chromatograph, or upon an allocation of representative components and associated physical properties as per Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2145, Table of Physical Constants for Hydrocarbons and Other Compounds of Interest to the Natural gas Industry, latest revision. The on-line gas chromatograph used for the analysis of Natural Gas shall be standardized daily. (e) Shipper shall have the right to obtain a duplicate sample of Shipper's Gas. If a difference between Transporter and Shipper's duplicate sample exceeds one-half percent (0.5%) in MMBtu, then Shipper shall have the right to call for retest and the analysis from the preceding period shall be used until the results can be verified or a representative sample is obtained and applied. Upon written request to Gas Measurement Services, the Shipper shall furnish the requesting Party with their natural gas sample, chromatographic gas analysis report, or any other information, which may be required to verify the other Party's analytical procedures or results. 17.8 Calibration. (a) Shipper shall have the right, at its sole cost and expense, to have a representative present at the time of any installing, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, testing, calibrating, or adjusting done in connection with the equipment used in measuring Gas deliveries hereunder. (b) At the frequencies of sampling tabulated above Shipper shall also calibrate or cause to be calibrated the meters and instruments used for measurement hereunder. Transporter shall give Shipper sufficient advance notice so Shipper may, at its election, have a representative present at such tests. In the event either Party shall notify the other Party that it desires a special test of any measurement equipment, the Parties shall cooperate to secure a prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment. The expense of any such special test, if requested, shall be borne by the Party requesting the test if the measuring equipment tested is found not to be in error or to be in composite error by not more than one percent. 17.9 Corrections. (a) If, upon test, the aggregate error of all measuring equipment, excluding gas chromatographs, is not in excess of two percent (2.0%), previous recordings of such equipment shall be considered accurate for computing deliveries to the Transporter. A calibration shall be performed on any measuring equipment found in error by an amount in excess of that specified in API Chapter 21.1 or any other level agreed to by both Parties. (b) If, upon test, any measuring equipment shall be found, in aggregate, to be inaccurate by an amount exceeding two percent (2.0%) of all measurement parameters and associated measuring equipment under review, at a recording corresponding to the average hourly rate of flow for the period since the last test, such equipment shall be corrected to zero error for any period which is known definitely, but in case the period is not known or agreed upon, such correction shall be for a period equal to one-half of the time elapsed since the date of the last test. (c) Where unacceptable measurement differences exist and all other tests have been conducted to remedy the error, the orifice meter run shall be inspected and tests shall be performed to verify compliance with current AGA Committee No. 3, Part 2, Specification and Installation Requirements, as amended from time to time. (d) If for any reason the meter is out of service or repair so that the quantity of Gas deliveries through such meter cannot be ascertained or computed from the readings thereof, the quantity of Gas so delivered during the period when the meter is out of service or repair shall be determined on the basis of the first of the following methods which is feasible, as agreed between the Parties. (i) By using the registration of any check measuring equipment, if such equipment is recording accurately. The Transporter shall witness and audit such measurement in the same manner that it would any custody transfer measurement equipment; (ii) By using the cumulative volumes from any field measurement source adjusting for historical differences or fuel consumption between the field meters and sales. (iii) By correcting the error, if possible, by calibration, tests, or mathematical calculation. (iv) By estimating the quantity received or delivered by receipts or deliveries during periods under similar conditions when the meter was verified to be registering correctly. 17.10 Prior Period Adjustment. All adjustments will be taken back to the delivery Month. A meter adjustment becomes a prior period adjustment after the final measurement close of the Month. All missing or late measurement data will be estimated and actual data will be treated as a prior period adjustment. The measuring Party is responsible for providing the estimated volume to be used. 17.11 Requesting Charts and Records. Each Party shall, upon request of the other, mail or deliver for checking and calculation all volume and temperature meter charts in its possession and used in the measurement of Gas received or delivered hereunder within thirty (30) days after the last chart for each billing period is removed from the meter. Such charts shall be returned within thirty (30) days after the receipt thereof. Where electric measurement is used for custody transfer of the Gas, the standard audit package will be supplied by the measuring Party. 17.12 Preservation of Records. Each Party shall preserve or cause to be preserved for mutual use all test data, charts or other similar records in accordance with the applicable rules and regulations of any regulatory bodies having jurisdiction with respect to the retention of such records, and, in any event, for at least five (5) years.

BBT BAMAGAS INTRASTATE, LLC Statement of Operating Conditions for Transportation Service Record: 19-Section 18 (Force Majeure) Issued: April 1, 2017 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: September 27, 2022 18. FORCE MAJEURE 18.1 Definition. Inability of either Party to perform shall be excused if and when, given the particulars of the circumstances, the disabled Party is unable to control, prevent, or overcome the cause thereof by the exercise of reasonable diligence and at a reasonable cost, including an inability caused by any act of God, nature, government, the need to maintain, repair, or replace equipment and facilities, or a third party, including outages or failures of utilities or communications equipment or services, or the inability to obtain necessary permits, servitudes, personnel, tools, equipment, or supplies ("Force Majeure"); provided, however, that performance by the Parties shall only be excused as to the particular duty or obligation to the extent affected by such Force Majeure. A Force Majeure shall be remedied by the disabled Party with all due diligence. Notwithstanding the foregoing, a Force Majeure shall not relieve: (a) The disabled Party of any obligation or duty under this Statement in the event of its failure to remedy the Force Majeure in an adequate manner and with all due diligence; (b) Either Party from its obligations to make payments of amounts then due; or (c) Either Party of any duty or obligation under this Statement not affected by the Force Majeure. 18.2 Notification. The Party experiencing a Force Majeure shall notify the other Party as soon as practicable after the occurrence of the Force Majeure and provide the other Party with information regarding the nature and extent of the Force Majeure and the expected duration of the Force Majeure. The Party experiencing the Force Majeure Condition shall keep the other Party apprised of the status of the Force Majeure. 18.3 Strikes. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the Party having the difficulty, and the requirement herein that any Force Majeure shall be remedied with all due diligence shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of opposing Party when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the Party having the difficulty.
